{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Finish Jira hard-delete -> outbound re-create (replaces lost epic-3e36)\n\n## Why\nOn a Jira hard-delete the reconciler preserves local content (ADR 0027/0028) BUT never re-creates the Jira\nissue. The path is broken at two joints:\n- **Key mismatch**: `route_inbound_probe` (reconcile.py:316-324, ARCHIVED_OR_MOVED branch) builds the\n  inbound-delete Mutation with `payload={\"reason\": \"hard_delete\", ...}`, but `_apply_inbound_delete`\n  (apply_inbound.py:184) reads `payload.get(\"probe_outcome\", \"out_of_window\")` â€” so the hard_delete branch is\n  UNREACHABLE (always defaults to out_of_window).\n- **Dropped follow-on**: even when the branch is reached it builds a `follow_on`\n  (apply_inbound.py:202-210, keys `direction/action/target/local_id`, `action=\"create_after_hard_delete\"`, NO\n  `fields`), but the applier consumer (applier.py:467-468) only handles `follow_on.get(\"kind\")==\"suppress_pair\"`\n  â€” the `create_after_hard_delete` follow-on (which sets `action`, not `kind`) is silently ignored. This is the\n  `epic-3e36` TODO (apply_inbound.py:209-210).\n\n## What (one coherent path: inbound detect -> standard outbound CREATE mutation)\n1. **Canonical key = `reason`.** Change `_apply_inbound_delete` (apply_inbound.py:184) to read\n   `payload.get(\"reason\") or payload.get(\"probe_outcome\", \"out_of_window\")` (accept `reason`, keep back-compat).\n   Update ALL `probe_outcome` fixture sites in `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/mutate/test_inbound_leaf_bodies.py`\n   â€” verified there are exactly TWO: line 281 (`payload = {\"probe_outcome\": outcome}`, the parametrized test\n   covering all four outcomes incl. hard_delete) and line 332 (`payload={\"probe_outcome\": \"redirect\", ...}`).\n   Both must carry `reason` (parametrize both keys, or switch to `reason`). (The review's guess of line 289 is\n   stale â€” no `probe_outcome` there on current main.)\n2. **Reconstruct `fields`.** The follow-on carries `local_id` but not `fields`, and `create_one`\n   (dispatch_one.py:147-156, 168) REQUIRES a `mutation[\"fields\"]`. Fetch the still-present LOCAL ticket by\n   `local_id` and map it via `outbound_fields._map_local_to_jira_fields(ticket, binding_store, ...)`\n   (outbound_fields.py:112-117) â€” the SAME mapper the outbound differ uses (returns summary/description/\n   issuetype/priority/status/assignee/parent).\n   - **Lookup mechanism (explicit):** the applier inbound loop (applier.py:455-474) has NO `local_tickets` in\n     scope, and there is no by-id helper. `repo_root` IS in scope; read `<repo_root>/.tickets-tracker/<local_id>/\n     .cache.json` `state` directly (single-ticket, cheap), falling back to `reconcile_check.load_local_tickets`\n     only if the cache is absent.\n   - **Failure path:** wrap the `.cache.json` read in `try/except (json.JSONDecodeError, OSError)`. If the local\n     ticket is absent, the cache is malformed, or `_map_local_to_jira_fields` yields empty/no-summary, do NOT emit\n     a create â€” log + skip (a hard-deleted ticket with no local content is not re-creatable). Tested.\n3. **Wiring (dedicated pre-batch side-channel â€” must flow THROUGH `_apply_batch`).** Introduce a new\n   `pending_hard_delete_creates: list[dict]` local in `apply()` (declared next to `pending_bug_tickets` at\n   applier.py:453). In the inbound loop (L455-474), when `follow_on.get(\"action\")==\"create_after_hard_delete\"`,\n   build a batch-dict CREATE entry (a **dict**, NOT a typed `Mutation`, because `outbound_list` is already a\n   `list[dict]`) shaped like a normal outbound create â€” `{\"action\":\"create\",\"key\":<jira-target-or-\"\">,\n   \"local_id\":local_id,\"fields\":<mapped fields>}` (match the dict keys `_apply_batch`/`create_one` read: `fields`\n   + `local_id`; use `_mutation_to_batch_dict` if you build a Mutation first) â€” and append it to\n   `pending_hard_delete_creates`.\n   Then, AFTER `outbound_list` is materialised + suppression-filtered (applier.py:486-490) and BEFORE the\n   `_apply_batch(outbound_list, â€¦)` dispatch (L495), do `outbound_list.extend(pending_hard_delete_creates)`.\n   **This is DELIBERATELY unlike `pending_bug_tickets`**, which drains in the `finally` AFTER `_apply_batch`\n   (L503-521) via a separate `in_process_cli` call and thus BYPASSES `create_one`. The re-create MUST go through\n   `_apply_batch` -> `create_one` so it gets JQL dedup + `bind_confirm`. It shares only the *collection* idea\n   (a side-channel list populated in the inbound loop), not the drain site. No mid-loop `create_one`, no\n   typed-dispatch bypass.\n\n### Follow-on dict schema (both discriminants coexist)\nThe applier's inbound-loop follow-on routing keys off TWO independent discriminants, kept as-is:\n- `follow_on[\"kind\"] == \"suppress_pair\"` -> `suppression.record(...)` (existing).\n- `follow_on[\"action\"] == \"create_after_hard_delete\"` -> the new re-create path (this ticket). Keys:\n  `direction, action, target, local_id` (no `fields` â€” reconstructed in step 2).\nA given follow-on carries exactly one of `kind`/`action`; the routing checks both independently.\n4. **Idempotency + deferral.** `create_one`'s JQL dedup (`labels = \"rebar-id:<local_id>\"`, dispatch_one.py:\n   194-219) prevents double-create on retry. If `rest_calls >= _REST_CALL_BUDGET` (=200, dispatch_one.py:97,\n   188-192) `create_one` issues zero REST calls, appends to `deferred_creates`, returns None -> the re-create\n   DEFERS to the next pass (same as the normal create path). Test BOTH partial-failure directions:\n   (a) create ok but a following rebind/confirm fails; (b) create deferred by budget exhaustion.\n5. **Stale reverse-index cleanup.** `bind_confirm(local_id, jira_key)` (binding_store.py:276-288) overwrites\n   `bindings[local_id][\"jira_key\"]` and sets `reverse[jira_key]=local_id` but never removes the OLD key's reverse\n   entry (no `rebind` method exists; only `unbind` pops reverse). Fix: at the TOP of `bind_confirm`, read\n   `old_key = entry.get(\"jira_key\")` BEFORE overwriting; if `old_key and old_key != jira_key`, `reverse.pop(old_key,\n   None)` in the SAME save. Edits `binding_store.py`.\n6. **Guard + housekeeping.** Guard the re-create so ONLY a genuine `reason==\"hard_delete\"` triggers it (redirect/\n   out_of_window/trash never re-create). Repoint/remove the `TODO(epic-3e36)` at apply_inbound.py:209-210. Update\n   ADR 0027/0028 to document the now-completed re-create behavior (inbound consumer injects an outbound CREATE\n   into the same pass). Clear the `.joe-janitor/report` flag if present.\n\n## Scope (files EDITED)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound.py` â€” key fix (read `reason`) + TODO repoint\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/applier.py` â€” consume `create_after_hard_delete`; NEW import\n  `from .outbound_fields import _map_local_to_jira_fields` (the new cross-module coupling lives HERE â€” applier ->\n  outbound_fields); local-ticket lookup; `pending_hard_delete_creates` injection into `outbound_list`\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/binding_store.py` â€” stale `reverse[old_key]` cleanup in `bind_confirm`\n- `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/mutate/test_inbound_leaf_bodies.py` â€” fixture key updates (L281, L332)\n- new test file `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_hard_delete_recreate.py` â€” consumer + rebind + failure + guard\n- `docs/adr/0027*.md` / `0028*.md` â€” document completed behavior\n\n**Read-only (NOT edited), noted for the coupling:** `outbound_fields.py` (`_map_local_to_jira_fields` is\nimported/called by applier.py, not modified); `dispatch_one.py` (`create_one` behavior relied on, not changed).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\nEach AC names its proving test (all under `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/`; run with\n`pytest tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/ -q`).\n- [ ] `_apply_inbound_delete` reads `reason` (canonical) with `probe_outcome` fallback; the hard_delete branch is\n      reachable from EITHER key. Both fixture sites (test_inbound_leaf_bodies.py L281, L332) updated. Proof:\n      `test_hard_delete_recreate.py::test_reason_key_enters_hard_delete_branch` AND\n      `::test_probe_outcome_key_still_enters_hard_delete_branch` (both keys asserted; the fallback is NOT dead).\n- [ ] The applier consumes `action==\"create_after_hard_delete\"`: fetches the local ticket by `local_id`,\n      reconstructs `fields` via `_map_local_to_jira_fields`, and injects a batch-dict CREATE into `outbound_list`\n      before `_apply_batch`. Proof: `test_hard_delete_recreate.py::test_recreate_injected_into_outbound_batch`\n      asserts the fake acli client records a `create_issue` for the local_id (i.e. it flowed through `create_one`,\n      not a post-batch bypass).\n- [ ] Consumer failure path: local ticket absent / `.cache.json` malformed / no mappable summary -> log + skip,\n      no create emitted. Proof: `::test_recreate_skips_when_local_ticket_absent` and\n      `::test_recreate_skips_on_malformed_cache`.\n- [ ] Idempotency + deferral: JQL dedup prevents a double-create on retry; REST-budget exhaustion defers to the\n      next pass. Proof: `::test_recreate_jql_dedup_no_double_create` (create-ok, second pass dedups) and\n      `::test_recreate_deferred_when_budget_exhausted`.\n- [ ] `bind_confirm` deletes the stale `reverse[old_key]` (read BEFORE overwrite) in the same save. Proof:\n      `test_binding_store.py::test_bind_confirm_rebind_drops_stale_reverse_key` asserts `reverse` has no dangling\n      old-key entry after a rebind.\n- [ ] Guard: only `reason==\"hard_delete\"` re-creates (redirect/out_of_window/trash do not). Proof:\n      `::test_non_hard_delete_branches_do_not_recreate` (parametrized over the other outcomes).\n- [ ] Housekeeping: `TODO(epic-3e36)` at apply_inbound.py:209-210 repointed/removed; ADR 0027/0028 updated to\n      document the completed re-create behavior; `.joe-janitor/report` flag cleared if present.\n- [ ] End-to-end test: a single reconcile pass driven from an inbound hard-delete probe result produces an\n      outbound CREATE for the still-present local ticket, asserted via the fake acli client's recorded create\n      call. Proof: `::test_hard_delete_recreate_end_to_end_one_pass` â€” distinct from the unit branch/consumer\n      tests (it drives the full `apply()` pass, not `_apply_inbound_delete` in isolation)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783555101303254001,"uuid":"300687a5-39af-40e6-9e8b-ddb145a629cc"}